## 🏗 ARCHITECTURE

### Pattern
MVC-inspired separation of concerns adapted for web applications.

### Enforced Structure

```
project-root/
│
├── .readmeIA               ← This file. AI context. Always at root.
├── README.md               ← Human-facing documentation
│
├── config/                 ← All configuration. No config leaking into src/
│   ├── app.config.js       ← Application-level settings
│   ├── db.config.js        ← Database connection config
│   └── .env.example        ← Environment variable template (never commit .env)
│
├── src/
│   ├── controllers/        ← Business logic. One file per domain entity.
│   ├── models/             ← Data schemas and database interaction
│   ├── views/              ← Templates, pages, partials
│   ├── routes/             ← Route definitions only. No logic here.
│   ├── middleware/         ← Auth, validation, logging middleware
│   └── services/           ← External API calls, shared utilities
│
├── public/                 ← Static assets served directly
│   ├── css/                ← Stylesheets only. No inline styles in views.
│   │   ├── base/           ← Reset, typography, variables
│   │   ├── components/     ← Reusable component styles
│   │   └── pages/          ← Page-specific styles
│   ├── js/                 ← Client-side scripts only
│   │   ├── components/     ← UI component scripts
│   │   └── pages/          ← Page-specific scripts
│   └── assets/             ← Images, fonts, icons
│       ├── images/
│       └── fonts/
│
├── tests/
│   ├── unit/               ← One test file mirrors one src file
│   └── integration/        ← Full-flow tests
│
└── docs/                   ← Architecture decisions, API docs, diagrams
```

### Rules enforced by AI
- CSS lives in `public/css/`. Never in `views/` or `src/`.
- Client-side JS lives in `public/js/`. Never mixed with server logic.
- Config lives in `config/`. No hardcoded values in `src/`.
- Routes define paths and delegate to controllers. Zero business logic in routes.
- Models own data shape and DB queries. Controllers never query the DB directly.

---

## 📐 CONVENTIONS

### File Naming
| Type | Convention | Example |
|------|-----------|---------|
| Controllers | `camelCase.controller.js` | `userAuth.controller.js` |
| Models | `PascalCase.model.js` | `UserProfile.model.js` |
| Views | `kebab-case.view.html` | `user-dashboard.view.html` |
| CSS files | `kebab-case.css` | `nav-header.css` |
| JS client files | `camelCase.js` | `formValidation.js` |
| Config files | `domain.config.js` | `db.config.js` |
| Test files | `[name].test.js` | `userAuth.controller.test.js` |

### CSS
- Variables defined in `public/css/base/variables.css`
- BEM methodology: `.block__element--modifier`
- No inline styles. No `!important` except as last resort (must be commented).
- Mobile-first breakpoints.

### JavaScript
- `const` by default. `let` only when reassignment is required. Never `var`.
- Named exports over default exports.
- Async/await over promise chains.
- Functions named with verbs: `getUser`, `validateEmail`, `renderDashboard`.

### Git
- Branch format: `feature/short-description`, `fix/short-description`, `chore/short-description`
- Commit format: `type(scope): description` — e.g., `feat(auth): add JWT refresh logic`
- No direct commits to `main`.

